@node "intro" "The Joker."
@toc "main"

    Why to reinvent the wheel? Well, our wheel doesn't gather any moss, unlike
    MJoin and dechunker just to name a few. We here at the RRR's utilities
    division got so tired of waiting, and finally when we ran out of Pepsi,
    we got a vision from our Galactic masters, the purple toads, who instructed
    and gave us the technology to produce such a wonderful tool as Ms. Sapphire is.

    Here you are. The ultimate join command replacement, Ms. Sapphire. Not only she
    will join the files Ms. Onyx has made, but she'll also cheer you up with
    her cute remarks. ;)

@endnode

@node "req" "King Tut."
@toc "main"

    An Amiga with an 020 processor is required. Due to the heavy 32-bit calculations,
    we decided not to include a limited 000 version. All you 68000 owners can
    use the MJoin and dechunker to your foul purposes.

    Also a nice chunk of memory is required due to the nature of our fast data
    joining routines. The more you have, the bigger files you can join.

@endnode

@node "usage" "The Scarface."
@toc "main"

    > join [FILENAME] [BASENAME] [ENTER]

    [FILENAME] - The file to be created from smaller files.
    [BASENAME] - Name for the smaller files. You must supply here the basename
                 without the .xxx - extension.
    [ENTER]    - The button found on most keyboards. The c64 has a Return button.



    > join RRR-CE.LHA RRR-CE [ENTER]

   -> RRR-CE.LHA (from RRR-CE.000, RRR-CE.001 ... etc...)


    When the program is running a panel will be shown.

          r[ū]       Done:   2       w[ ]

    The r stands for reading data and w for writing data. From these buttons
    you can see what the program is doing.

    Done shows the number of files that have been added to the [FILENAME]Āarchive.

    Note that you cannot stop Ms. Sapphire while she's decutting the file.
    She's so keen on pasting that it would be dangerous to try to interrupt her. ;)

@endnode

